What is a Reverse Proxy?
A reverse proxy is a server that receives client requests and forwards them to backend servers, then sends the response back to the client.

NGINX Reverse Proxy Configuration (Step by Step)
ğŸ¯ Goal of this stage

NGINX listens on port 80

Gunicorn runs internally on port 8000

Users access the app using browser â†’ port 80

They never see port 8000

ğŸ”¹ Step 1 â€” Confirm NGINX is installed

Run:

nginx -v


If not installed:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install nginx -y


Start & enable:

sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx


Test in browser:

http://<server-ip>


You should see NGINX Welcome Page âœ…

ğŸ”¹ Step 2 â€” Go to NGINX config directory
cd /etc/nginx/sites-available
ls


You will see:

default

ğŸ”¹ Step 3 â€” Create a config file for Flask app
sudo nano flaskapp


Paste  this configuration:

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name _;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;
    }
}

ğŸ” What this means (simple):

listen 80 â†’ NGINX listens on browser port

proxy_pass â†’ forwards request to Gunicorn

headers â†’ pass client info correctly

Save:

CTRL + X â†’ Y â†’ Enter

ğŸ”¹ Step 4 â€” Enable the site

Go to enabled sites:

cd /etc/nginx/sites-enabled
ls


Enable your app:

sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/flaskapp .


Remove default site:

sudo rm default

ğŸ”¹ Step 5 â€” Test NGINX configuration
sudo nginx -t


You must see:

syntax is ok
test is successful

ğŸ”¹ Step 6 â€” Restart NGINX
sudo systemctl restart nginx

ğŸ”¹ Step 7 â€” Final test (MOST IMPORTANT)

Make sure Gunicorn is running:

sudo ss -lntup | grep 8000


Now open browser:

http://<server-ip>


ğŸ‰ You should see your Flask app without port number
